Oil exploration has resumed at the Shell Oil Mining Licence (OML) 25, two years after it was shut down and occupied by women of Belema, Offion-Ama and Ngeje communities  in Akuku-toru Local Government Area of Rivers state. The Minister of State for Petroleum Resources, Timipre Sylva, officially opened the facility last weekend for oil exploration and production. The flow station operated jointly by Shell and Belema Oil was shut down by aggrieved host communities in August 2017 and occupied by the women of the area on the grouse that the operators of the oil facilities have not impacted positively on the host communities. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY Chief Silver assured the host communities that they will  not be taken for granted saying that  their interests will henceforth be paramount in new Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) signed with SPDC,  NNPC and other Joint Venture Partners to re-open the facility. The Managing Director of NNPC, Mele Kolo Kyari said he was in the community to ensure that peace return in the area. The Spokesman of the host communities and Chairman of Kula Council of Chiefs, King Kroma Eleki commended federal government for its intervention in the OML25 crisis. Chief Silver commissioned an NNPC/Belema Oil Joint Venture Water project, laid foundation for Kula Primary/Secondary School, Medical Centre among others.  Two years after, Belema women vacate OML25 flow station Belema communities occupy Shell facilities over ‘neglect’ Shell decries occupation of Belema flow station